{
  "doc_id": "18112",
  "text": "That ischemic preconditioning (IPC) and postconditioning (PoC) reduce infarct size acutely [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] and long term (50) The reasons underlying this \"species or size discrepancy\" have not been determined but may relate to species differences in 1) myocardial metabolism and the supply/demand mismatch that defines the severity of ischemia, 2) the complement of endogenous antioxidants expressed in the animal model, 3) the role of inflammatory cells during reperfusion, 4) effectiveness of the PoC algorithm for each species, which is likely multifactoral, but may be related in part to the rate in which reperfusion injury events occur. Relevant to point number 4, for example, Iliodromitis et al. [CITATION_7] found that the failure of PoC to reduce infarct size reported in the study by Schwartz and Lagrahna (57) in the pig model may be related to an insufficient number of reperfusion-occlusion cycles. However, cycles ranging from 30 to 60 s have been used in human studies with similar reductions in infarct size. Furthermore, Halkos et al. [CITATION_8] found that IPC and PoC exerted similar reduction in infarct size in the canine model, whereas in the rat IPC exerts greater infarct reduction than does PoC. Halkos et al. [CITATION_9] also showed that the cardioprotection by PoC was not additive to that of IPC in the canine model of left anterior descending coronary artery (LAD) occlusion and reperfusion. However, Yang et al. [CITATION_10] found that infarct size reduction with IPC and PoC were additive if ischemic times were prolonged in the rabbit model. Whether such additive protection is unmasked with prolonged coronary occlusion in which each strategy is ineffective by itself, or whether this is a species-dependent effect, is not clear and warrants further investigation. The entire question of the optimal algorithm and durations of reperfusion and ischemic segments of the PoC stimulus is open.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "24825458",
    "[CITATION_2]": "20865897",
    "[CITATION_3]": "27274809",
    "[CITATION_4]": "167325",
